<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-26T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-26T04:00:00-05:00" n="1280" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1280">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/4–2649: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-26T17:00:00+08:00">April 26,
                                    1949—5 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received April 26—9:30 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1368. Neither Admiral Badger nor I have ordered anyone leave Shanghai.
                            Mr. Flanley spoke to ITT referring to final warning issued by ConGen
                            (ConGentel 1342, April 25) and to telephone conversation re key
                            Telephone Co. personnel whom we agreed last December to evacuate in
                            final evacuation if they so desired.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>